# Negative guards for the baseline fixture (testdata/e2e/vulnerable/00-baseline.yaml),
# checked against the standard-preset full scan (.tmp/e2e-report-full/findings.json).
#
# Each line is a finding-ID prefix that must be ABSENT. A line matches a finding
# when the finding's id equals the line or starts with "<line>:". So a bare rule
# ID bans every instance of that rule, while a rule:subject prefix bans one
# specific instance. Lines starting with '#' and blank lines are skipped.
#
# This is the instance-level counterpart to the *.ruleset golden: the golden
# pins the rule-ID SET, but a rule can fire legitimately for one subject and be a
# false positive for another, which only a per-instance guard can catch.

# Issue #48: a namespace-scoped RoleBinding granting `create rolebindings` must
# NOT be modeled as a path to cluster-admin. It legitimately yields a
# NAMESPACE-ADMIN path (asserted positively in kind-e2e.sh), just not
# CLUSTER-ADMIN.
KUBE-PRIVESC-PATH-CLUSTER-ADMIN:ServiceAccount/rbac-ns-fixtures/sa-ns-rolebinding-mutate

# The psa-suppressed namespace carries pod-security.kubernetes.io/enforce=restricted
# (set during the e2e after rollout), so the policy-engine posture finding must
# self-suppress: KUBE-ADMISSION-NO-POLICY-ENGINE-001 fires only when NO admission
# control is present anywhere.
KUBE-ADMISSION-NO-POLICY-ENGINE-001

# Default --admission-mode=suppress must drop the privileged-pod finding for the
# psa-suppressed namespace, because its enforce=restricted label would block the
# spec at admission time.
KUBE-ESCAPE-001:Deployment:psa-suppressed:psa-priv-app
